(122, '4327-00', 'Bramcote Unity Park', 'Video creation utilising new 2d and 3d illustrative assets and the drone footage supplied to\ncreate a community awareness video showcasing the new multi-functional green open public space which will be\nideal for community events, walks for young and old, wildlife and connectivity to the wider surrounding areas.\n\n\nThe basic content is to incorporate - \n\n- explain in detail the unity of the parks across the ridge\n- an overview of the local area incorporating animated labels of local features\n- animated highlighting of walking routes around the open space\n- transitioning drone footage with 3d\n\n\nVIDEO TEXT (can be summerised down)\nKey benefits to the public (this will be shown as text on the video)\n\nOverall breakdown of park areas - \n    - Alexandrina Plantation = 3.57 hectares\n    - Sandy Lane LNR = 5.71 hectares\n    - Future park off Thoresby Road = 3.67 hectares \n    - Bramcote Unity Park = 2.85 hectares  \n\n• 7 acres of new publicly accessible woodland - quantify as a percentage. \n• Minimum £1m public parkland investment to deliver new community park\n• Protection of existing woodland and creation of additional woodland areas\n• Enhancement of woodland ecology\n• Unity of existing recreational areas\n• Addition of 1.3km of publicly accessible formal footpath added to the existing network of 1.5km across the Alexandrina Plantation and Sandy Lane LNR.  Land off Thoresby Road park, potential of additional 0.8km. Show as percentage.\n\nKey Section that explains bramcote unity park I.e the amalgamation of the deddington plantation with the alexandrine plantation, the privately owned central section and the sandy lane nature reserve. This is the  grand vision and the central missing section wont happen without capital expenditure and ongoing maintenance funding. The result is unifying land and people to create one fabulous park for all to enjoy.\n\nOverall facts:\n• a net increase of 632 trees planted, which represents 12 times more trees than currently on site for the creation of a new woodland where invasive species will be removed, screen planting and enhancement of the existing woodland. \n• 8 trees removed\n• New ponds\n• Approx. 10No. bird boxes throughout park \n• 2No. bee hives.  \n• Bird hide at high point of site with new woodland planting to allow for framed view. \n• Woodland play at entrances. Feature entrances incorporating artwork.  \n• Informative signage throughout park to aid navigation. • Introduction of 11 wildlife ponds. \n\n', '2019-04-09', '2019-05-09', 46, '2019-04-05', 11, 'open', '', 0, '', 0),
